isk-taking gradually developed gendered and racial limits and then spread from leisure activities to the consideration of elections as "races" and business as a "game." The result reorients the standard narrative about the rise of commercial popular culture to question the influence of ideas such as "gentility" and "respectability," and to put men like P. T. Barnum at the end instead of the beginning of the process, unveiling a new take on the creation of the white male republic of the early nineteenth century in which sporting activities lie at the center and not the margins of economic and political history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSportsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aSportsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSportsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 4aSports & Games. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aPoliticized entertainment, early america, theater history, business history, political and economic power of wealth,.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501714214?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501714214423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501714214/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles